        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> > Does `nvim_get_chan_info()` provide the relevant information?\r\n> \r\n> 👍 as hinted in [#14986 (comment)](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/14986#issuecomment-1676347598) ,\r\n> \r\n>     * The main missing piece is a way to get the result (error code) of the terminal process.\r\n>       \r\n>       * Add a `code` field to the result of `nvim_get_chan_info`.\r\n>       * ⚠️ Currently, when a process exits, Nvim destroys the job info, so `nvim_get_chan_info()` won't work.\r\n>         \r\n>         * To fix that, the _minimum_ interface is to change the internal channels/jobs list to keep ring buffer of the last N channels, instead of destroying the channel immediately.\r\n>         * Deprecate `nvim_list_chans`.\r\n>         * Deprecate `nvim_get_chan_info`.\r\n>         * Introduce `nvim_chan_get(channelId, opts): List<Dict>`\r\n> \r\n>     * The default 'statusline' should show the exit code (e.g. `Exit code: 0`). Users with a custom statusline can get the exit code via `nvim_chan_get()`.\r\n\r\nInstead of altering the nvim API, wouldn't it be better to add the exit code as a statusline item (e.g. %e) for users with a custom statusline?",
